# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#  .env.example — HTML Directory Scraper
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
#  Copy this file to .env and fill in your values:
#    cp .env.example .env
#
#  NEVER commit .env to Git — it is listed in .gitignore.
#  This file (.env.example) is safe to commit: it contains no real values.
#
#  Values set here override the equivalent keys in config.yaml at runtime.
#  The scraper loads .env automatically via python-dotenv.
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════


# Session cookies for sites that require authentication or cookie-based state.
#
# How to capture your cookies:
#   1. Log in to the target site in Chrome or Firefox.
#   2. Open DevTools (F12) → Network tab → reload the page.
#   3. Click any request to the target domain → Headers tab.
#   4. Find the "Cookie:" line under Request Headers.
#   5. Copy the entire value (everything after "Cookie: ") and paste below.
#
# The scraper injects these cookies into every HTTP request it makes.
# Cookies expire (typically 24–72 hours) — refresh this value if you start
# receiving HTTP 401 or 403 responses.
#
# Example (do not use real values here):
#   SCRAPER_COOKIES=session_id=abc123; auth_token=xyz456; csrftoken=def789
SCRAPER_COOKIES=
